[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Moore is a 58-year-old male from Port Gibson Billerica, who experienced a single episode of rectal bleeding on the evening of February 16, 2010, following a loose bowel movement. He was scheduled to have his annual physical close to that time, and he asked to have his lab work performed the following morning at his local provider's office.  He was then seen in clinic, and due to his rectal bleeding it was decided to admit him to the local hospital.  He was not anemic at that time. They prepped him the following day for a colonoscopy which was his first colon screening and was performed to the cecum.  This revealed a "very large rectal cancer" close to the anal verge. Biopsies were performed with pathology slides reviewed here revealing invasive grade 3 of 4 adenocarcinoma.  The colonoscopy was also notable for sigmoid and descending colon diverticulosis.  He denies having diverticulitis. He has been off his 81-mg prophylactic aspirin since this episode.
Mr. Moore has not undergone staging studies.  He was seen locally, and it was discussed that he likely will need an abdominoperineal resection with permanent colostomy, and the possibility of neoadjuvant therapy was discussed.  He has decided, however, he would like an evaluation and surgery here.  He has no family history of colorectal cancer and has not had recent weight-loss.  He has not been more fatigued.  His bowel habits have changed over the last couple months in that he has noticed his stools have been more loose with occasional diarrhea.  Prior to two-months ago, he typically moved his bowels twice-a-day, and they were formed. He has not had additional bleeding since his episode on the 16th.  He denies fecal incontinence or hemorrhoid problems.  He denies rectal and abdominal pain.  He did not experience pain with the bleeding episode on the 16th.
Separately, he brings a copy of his lab work performed prior to his hospitalization on February 16.  This reveals an elevated PSA at 4.88 with the range at Veterans Affairs Sepulveda Ambulatory Hospital being 0 to 4.  He also brings his lab work from the prior year.  On January 7, 2009, his PSA was 2.32.  He has a family history of prostate cancer in his father who developed this at age 72 and underwent a radical prostatectomy.  There was a question about the surgical margins and approximately 10 to 12 years later he had to undergo external-beam radiation therapy and now is doing well.  Mr. Moore believes his PSAs for the last several years since age 50 have been normal.  He denies hematuria, nocturia, or urinary incontinence.  There was a time approximately six to eight months ago when he was having difficulty obtaining an erection which lasted three-to-four months, and he was given a Viagra.  This ended up resolving spontaneously, and he has been doing well currently and never used the Viagra.

